### Variable Comments And Current Implementation Status

- `environment`
  - comment: deployment environment used to separate production from development and staging traffic
  - use on: all mobile, backend, and website analytics events
  - current status: mobile and backend already include it; website `TrackingProvider` now auto-enriches tracked website events and page views with `environment`
- `platform`
  - comment: coarse client platform identifier such as `ios`, `android`, `web`, `lambda`, or `ecs`
  - use on: all analytics events
  - current status: mobile and backend already include it; website `TrackingProvider` now auto-enriches tracked website events and page views with `platform = web`
- `source`
  - comment: high-level origin of the event stream, used to distinguish app, backend, and website traffic
  - use on: all analytics events
  - current status: mobile and backend already include it; website `TrackingProvider` now auto-enriches tracked website events and page views with `source = website`
- `trip_id`
  - comment: stable trip entity identifier for trip engagement funnels and trip-to-booking analysis
  - use on: `trip_viewed`, `trip_details_viewed`, `trip_stats_viewed`, `trip_created`, `trip_updated`, booking-adjacent events when a booking is tied to a known trip
  - current status: already present in shared schemas and already passed in core trip flows; still needs live-production verification for consistency
- `search_id`
  - comment: stable search/session identifier used to join `search_started` to downstream search/planning events
  - use on: `search_started`, `search_completed`, `search_failed`, `search_abandoned`, and any planning event that is clearly derived from one travel search
  - current status: implemented in shared schemas; mobile `useTravelAnalytics` now persists the generated `search_id` from `search_started` into `search_completed` even if callers do not manually thread it back
- `booking_id`
  - comment: stable booking entity identifier for conversion funnels and booking support/debugging
  - use on: `booking_started`, `booking_completed`, `booking_failed`, `booking_abandoned`, `flight_booking_completed`, payment-adjacent events
  - current status: already present in shared schemas and backend booking events; treat backend-confirmed booking events as source of truth
- `provider`
  - comment: booking/search vendor or fulfillment source such as `amadeus`, `skybird`, or `priceline`
  - use on: booking and search events where the upstream system matters for ops, conversion, or reliability analysis
  - current status: already supported; value vocabulary should remain normalized across mobile and backend
- `booking_type`
  - comment: canonical booking category such as `flight`, `hotel`, or `car`
  - use on: all booking lifecycle and conversion events
  - current status: already used on backend booking truth events; continue to avoid ad hoc variants
- `trigger_event`
  - comment: the meaningful event that caused `user_active` to fire for that local day
  - use on: `user_active` only
  - current status: implemented locally in mobile analytics; needed for debugging active-user semantics
- `screen_name`
  - comment: stable semantic screen identifier for screen-level usage and attribution, not raw route noise
  - use on: `screen_viewed`, modal/surface views, performance events, and interaction events where screen context matters
  - current status: already implemented broadly; mobile `unified-analytics.ts` now also normalizes common camelCase aliases like `screenName` -> `screen_name` at the tracking boundary so dashboards do not split the same screen into near-duplicates. Additional app-side coverage now explicitly adds stable `screen_name` context to `settings_opened`, `trip_stats_viewed`, `trip_details_viewed`, and `app_menu_action`.

Additional normalization now implemented in mobile analytics:

- common camelCase app properties are normalized to canonical snake_case before dispatch
- examples:
  - `conversationId` -> `conversation_id`
  - `messageLength` -> `message_length`
  - `inputMethod` -> `input_method`
  - `initiatedBy` -> `initiated_by`
  - `requestType` -> `request_type`
  - `planningType` -> `planning_type`
  - `hasDateRange` -> `has_date_range`
  - `responseTime` -> `response_time_ms`
- reason: this reduces dashboard fragmentation caused by mixed property vocabularies across app call sites

If cleanly available later, these would improve segmentation:

- `org_id`
- `workspace_id`
- `plan_tier`
- `user_type`

